

Setting up JUnit --  Test driven development and Logging framework

Step 1: Create a New Java Project
In your IDE:

IntelliJ IDEA: File → New → Project → select "Maven" (or "Java" with Maven support) → give it a name like JUnitBasics → Finish.
Eclipse: File → New → Maven Project → check "Create a simple project" → fill in Group Id / Artifact Id → Finish.

This gives you a standard Maven folder structure:
JUnitBasics/
├── pom.xml
└── src/
    ├── main/java/      ← your actual classes go here
    └── test/java/      ← your test classes go here


Step 2: Add the JUnit Dependency
Open pom.xml and add the dependency inside the <dependencies> tag (create that tag if it doesn't exist yet):
xml<project>
    ...
    <dependencies>
        <dependency>
            <groupId>junit</groupId>
            <artifactId>junit</artifactId>
            <version>4.13.2</version>
            <scope>test</scope>
        </dependency>
    </dependencies>
</project>
Notes:

scope=test means this library is only available when compiling/running tests, not your main application code — 
keeps your production build lean.
After saving pom.xml, tell Maven to re-download dependencies:

IntelliJ: click the little Maven "reload" icon (circular arrows) in the Maven tool window.
Eclipse: right-click project → Maven → Update Project.
Command line: mvn install



Using Gradle instead of Maven, add this to build.gradle:
groovydependencies {
    testImplementation 'junit:junit:4.13.2'
}
test {
    useJUnit()
}


Step 3: Create a Simple Class to Test
Under src/main/java, create a class, e.g. Calculator.java:
javapackage com.example;

public class Calculator {
    public int add(int a, int b) {
        return a + b;
    }

    public int subtract(int a, int b) {
        return a - b;
    }
}


Step 4: Create a Test Class
Under src/test/java (mirror the same package), create CalculatorTest.java:
javapackage com.example;

import org.junit.Test;
import static org.junit.Assert.assertEquals;

public class CalculatorTest {

    @Test
    public void testAdd() {
        Calculator calc = new Calculator();
        int result = calc.add(2, 3);
        assertEquals(5, result);
    }
}
Key points about this class:

@Test marks a method as a test case — JUnit will run it automatically.
The class itself needs no special annotation, just plain Java.
Naming convention: test classes are usually named <ClassName>Test.

Step 5: Run the Test

IntelliJ/Eclipse: right-click the test class or method → "Run".
Maven CLI: run mvn test from the project root.

You should see output confirming the test passed (green checkmark in IDE, or BUILD SUCCESS / Tests run: 1, Failures: 0 in the terminal).
